Abstract. - We find a new long-range inkaction between foreign inclusions (e.g. mobile
proteins) in a fluid membrane which is mediated by the membrane itself. The interaction falls off as l/R4, can be attractive or repulsive depending on the temperature and the elastic properties
of the inclusion and the membrane, and for large distances is large compared with electrostatic,
van der Waals,and other lipid-mediated forces.
Fluid membranes in an aqueous environment are characterized by large fluctuations in their shape[l]. Following the description of membranes as flexible sheets controlled by bending rigidities[2], these shape fluctuations have been extensively studied in the theoretical literature. These studies generaIly assume the membrane has uniform elastic
constants. On the other hand, biologically relevant membranes are highly heterogeneous131: cell membranes contain attached or embedded proteins and the constituent surfactant molecules usually span a broad spectrum of lipids. Many membrane proteins are mobile and the phase behavior (e.g. aggregation) of such systems and of lipid concentration
inhomogeneities is of considerable biological importance(9.Particularly intriguing is the
relation between the phase behavior and shape fluctuations. Aggregation of membrane inclusions is expected to be controlled by lipid affinity, direct
interactions (electrostatic and van der Waals forces), and indirect interactions mediated by
the membrane. There is an obvious interplay between the latter interactions and membrane shape fluctuations. Previous calculations associated with membrane deformations led to
